<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40047d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40047d">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40047d"> 47(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> demonic possession</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In more recent times a great variety of opinions has been expressed on this subject. J. S. Semler denied the reality of demonic possession, and held that Christ in his language accommodated himself to the views of the sick whom he was seeking to cure. <br>&hellip; W. M. Alexander in his book on demonic possession maintains that &ldquo;the confession of Jesus as the Messiah or Son of God is the classical criterion of genuine demonic possession&rdquo; (p. 150), and argues that as &ldquo;the Incarnation indicated the establishment of the kingdom of heaven upon earth,&rdquo; there took place &ldquo;a countermovement among the powers of darkness,&rdquo; of which &ldquo;genuine demonic possession was one of the manifestations&rdquo; (p. 249). <small> &ldquo;DEVIL&rdquo; <a name="EBDV" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBDV"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) VIII 122</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
